					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/zyn" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1404533); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1404533&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610219299" alt="Zyn" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1404533)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/zyn" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1404533); return false;" >Zyn</a></span> <span class="odate time_1552534534 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">14 Mar 2019 03:35</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4183915">
									

<p>General note, the context/reasons behind the two new policies:</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">Click&nbsp;to&nbsp;show</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">click&nbsp;to&nbsp;hide</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>1. By far the most commonly seen response to first-time pieces is &quot;the main idea is not interesting&quot;. This is consistent across both the draft forums and the mainsite (per preserved critique in the deletions announcement threads).</p>
<p>The greenlighting policy intends to increase awareness of the importance of having unique and intriguing concepts for all types of writing on the SCP wiki, and hopefully save new authors frustration by helping them enter the drafting stage with an idea that they can already expect some measure of community interest and success from.</p>
<p>2. Staff has often seen complaints that because we try to ensure that all drafts receive at least one quality review, a lot of staff manpower/hours go into drafts that contain a lot of simple errors and would not do well on the mainsite without being rewritten entirely.</p>
<p>The auto-defer policy intends to focus reviewer attention on drafts that authors have put time and effort into polishing to a certain essential level of quality. Also, we would like to emphasize that it is the author's responsibility to be able to identify most simple errors on their own and be familiar with various aspects of writing for the SCP wiki, rather than relying solely on reviewers for tutoring basics.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Tl;dr</p>
<p>1. is there because we see &quot;get the idea checked&quot; happen way, way too often with drafts already. Conceptualization is important!</p>
<p>2. is there because we want authors to be able to teach themselves the basics, so they don't need to run for a reviewer to help them with every little thing.</p>

							</div>

								
