			<div class="content" id="post-content-4230485">
									

<p>I have created my account here quite recently. I had a fun idea and thought it would be fun to put together a proper SCP, as a little writing side-project. Sadly exams got in the way and I was too busy to come back to the idea, at times I genuinely didn't feel like working on it as it is an extensive task on its own.</p>
<p>Today I decided to jump back on and get into writing. I log in and start going through the 'How to Write SCP' guide once again just to make sure I don't do anything wrong. Then I see the updated rules regarding new authors.<br />
All first-time authors must get their concepts reviewed (either in the Ideas and Brainstorming forum or the IRC chatrooms) and greenlighted by two experienced reviewers before the authors may request feedback on a full draft in the Drafts and Critiques forum.</p>
<p>My heart sank. I was excited to write an SCP, not to discuss a general concept of my idea. Writing itself requires a lot of time and effort, judging something just from an idea is extremely close-minded and quite frankly it is very discouraging to forbid newcomers from writing their own SCPs. Opinions are inherently subjective and asking anyone to judge a piece of writing from a concept is ludicrous.</p>
<p>Generalizing an idea you are not allowed to write also quite difficult as anyone with a bit of experience in writing can attest that while writing a lot of new and interesting ideas come while your fingers are hitting the keyboard. It is impossible to summarize in a few sentences.</p>
<p>I've not participated in the community before, but I have done my research on how it began and the ideals it stood for. This does not feel like the same community or even the same basic idea as the things I have heard.</p>

