					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/pedantique" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(3118444); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=3118444&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610219299" alt="Pedantique" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=3118444)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/pedantique" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(3118444); return false;" >Pedantique</a></span> <span class="odate time_1556273915 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">26 Apr 2019 10:18</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4230498">
									

<blockquote>
<p>Opinions are inherently subjective and asking anyone to judge a piece of writing from a concept is ludicrous.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Any writing you do on the site will be judged by the community once posted, so this is going to be a hard one to avoid.</p>
<p>The conceptual and draft review processes are intended to help new authors (and experienced ones) write better in general and for the site in particular. Readers here have expectations that may not be apparent on casual observation, some concepts have been done to death, and there's generally a need for guidance on first works.</p>
<p>The greenlighting process in particular was instituted due to a truly overwhelming number of drafts being posted daily that were flawed on a fundamental level. While it's true that most (if not all) ideas can work with proper execution, new authors generally aren't the ones to due that due to unfamiliarity with the site's culture, the larger body of extant works, etc. The current system allows for more attention to be devoted to drafts that actually merit further development.</p>
<p>Instead of looking at the process as an obstacle to be overcome, I would strongly recommend looking at it as an opportunity to get feedback from experienced authors on your core concept. It's much easier to hammer out a draft than succinctly summarize an idea, but that's usually because the draft itself covers up fundamental issues with the concept.</p>
<p>Lastly, as to the site not being the same in the past, I wasn't around then and couldn't comment. New people arrive though, old people leave, and rules need to change in accordance with modern needs. It was a much smaller website then, and frankly the writing standards seem to have been somewhat lower.</p>

							</div>

								
					
